  "text": "Hybrid (dentata-crispula) hybrid (crispula-serrata) Fig. 2 Distribution of principal-components scores (PC1 and PC2) in analysis on Phyllonorycter and Tuberculatus compositions of 35 trees at the scaffolding-system sites. Trees were tentatively identified (see text and Table 3) through backcross. In addition, at least hybrids between Q. dentata and Q. crispula harbored both Q. dentata-and Q. crispula-specific herbivores. These results suggest that the hybrids could act as ''bridges'' for host shift of pest insects [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . However, it is not known whether the host shift truly occurred between these oak species. Studies on genetic differentiation of herbivore populations on parental and hybrid trees may help to answer this question.",
